additional_context:
Let S be the set of limit points of (p_{n+1}-p_n)/\log n. This problem asks whether S=[0,∞]. Although this conjecture remains unproven, a lot is known about S. Some highlights:
{UL}
{LI}∞∈ S by Westzynthius' result \cite{We31} on large prime gaps,{/LI}
{LI}0∈ S by the work of Goldston, Pintz, and Yildirim \cite{GPY09} on small prime gaps,{/LI}
{LI}Erdős \cite{Er55} and Ricci \cite{Ri56} independently showed that S has positive Lebesgue measure,{/LI}
{LI} Hildebrand and Maier \cite{HiMa88} showed that S contains arbitrarily large (finite) numbers,{/LI}
{LI} Pintz \cite{Pi16} showed that there exists some small constant c>0 such that [0,c]⊂ S,{/LI}
{LI} Banks, Freiberg, and Maynard \cite{BFM16} showed that at least 12.5\% of [0,∞) belongs to S,{/LI}
{LI} Merikoski \cite{Me20} showed that at least 1/3 of [0,∞) belongs to S, and that S has bounded gaps.{/LI}
{/UL}
In \cite{Er65b}, \cite{Er85c}, and \cite{Er97c} Erdős asks whether S is everywhere dense (but Weisenberg notes that clearly S is closed so this is equivalent to asking whether S=[0,∞]).

See also [234].

References

